One issue with the current API is that it doesn't provide an intuitive order for the overlayChildren. In general I would expect tree order to be respected as the paint order: if I have a column with two children, the second one paints on top of the first.
However, with this API the paint order is actually chronological by order of when the portals were created. For example, in this code the "BOTTOM" (earlier) child ends up on top of the "TOP" (later) child because the LayoutBuilder changes the order in which we walk the tree:
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      home: MyHomePage(),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyHomePage({super.key});

  @override
  State<MyHomePage> createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: <Widget>[
            LayoutBuilder(
              builder: (BuildContext context, BoxConstraints constraints) => OverlayPortal(
                overlayInfo: OverlayInfo.of(context),
                overlayChild: Positioned(
                  top: 50.0,
                  left: 50.0,
                  width: 200.0,
                  height: 100.0,
                  child: Container(
                    color: Colors.yellow,
                    child: Text('BOTTOM'),
                  ),
                ),
                child: Container(
                  color: Colors.orange,
                  child: Text('first source'),
                ),
              ),
            ),
            OverlayPortal(
              overlayInfo: OverlayInfo.of(context),
              overlayChild: Positioned(
                top: 75.0,
                left: 75.0,
                width: 200.0,
                height: 100.0,
                child: Container(
                  color: Colors.teal,
                  child: Text('TOP'),
                ),
              ),
              child: Container(
                color: Colors.blue,
                child: Text('second source'),
              ),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

@Hixie @goderbauer do you think the following API would be expressive enough for specifying the z-index/paint order?
// OverlayInfo renamed. You should not retain an `OverlayLocation` between rebuilds as it can go stale.
class OverlayLocation implements Comparable {  
  // Get the overlay location above this location in terms of paint order. 
  OverlayLocation get locationAbove; 

  // Get the OverlayLocation of the given BuildContext
  // Each OverlayEntry and overlayChild provides an OverlayLocation via an inherited widget.
  static OverlayLocation? of({ required BuildContext above }) => above.dependOnInheritedWidgetOfExactType()!;

  static int compare(lhs, rhs) => ... // throws if on different Overlays
}

class OverlayPortal { 
  // Just the existing named constructor renamed. No actual API changes.
  OverlayPortal.after({
     OverlayLocation location,
     // .. child, overlayChild,
  });
}
To force certain paint order when there may be layout builders:
Widget build(context) { 
  final child1Location = OverlayLocation.above(context);
  final child2Location = child1Location.locationAbove;
  final child3Location = child2Location.locationAbove;

  return Column([
    OverlayPortal.after(child1Location), 
    LayoutBuilder((_, _) =>  OverlayPortal.after(child2Location), 
    OverlayPortal.after(child3Location), 
  ]);
}
To express that a widget needs to be painted above both A and B
Widget build(context) { 
  return A(builder: (contextA) { 
     B(builder: (contextB) { 
       final locationA = OverlayLocation.of(contextA);
       final locationB = OverlayLocation.of(contextB);
       return OverlayPortal.after(
           location: locationA > locationB ? locationA : locationB,
          //... 
       );
     });
  });
}
So basically as an overlayChild you can specify that you want to be painted after another OverlayEntry/OverlayChild as long as you can see their buildcontext. Didn't expose an int z-index  in the public API since then you kinda have to stick to the number you initially choose.

One thing we could do is make key a required parameter of type ZIndex, a new class which has an interface like this:
class ZIndex extends GlobalObjectKey<_OverlayPortalState> implements Comparable<ZIndex> {
  // some constants such that anything minted from top is above anything minted from
  // default is above anything minted from bottom
  static const SZindex default = ...;
  static const SZindex top = ...;
  static const SZindex bottom = ...;

  ZIndex below() { ... } // mints a new instance that is just below this one (and above any earlier instances created this way)
  ZIndex above() { ... } // the opposite

  void dispose() { ... } // makes the ZIndex unusable
  ...
}

Because it implements GlobalObjectKey and is used as a key you can never have two widgets with the same z-index. Because any ZIndex always has a defined relationship to all others, you can never have two instances that are equal. Because the way to mint them is to specify the relationship to an existing ZIndex, you can always predict the order.
Implementing this would be tricky, you'd probably want to maintain a linked list where each ZIndex has a number representing its position in the sort order, and when you mint a new one you mint it with a number between the two ZIndex instances defining it, and if you ever run out of numbers you renumber the entire list...

