This creates an error-prone API as it makes it easy to end up in the following situation (e.g. after a refactoring):
var mediaQuery = MediaQuery.of(context, MediaQueryAspect.padding);

// ... lots of other lines of code

var size = mediaQuery.size;

// do something with size.
Now I may be surprised that my widget is actually not rebuilding when size changes. This problem will be frustrating to debug.
To resolve this, we'd have to create an API that only gives you access to the MediaQuery aspect that you actually depend on.

@moffatman Maybe my next question will sound silly but why can't we convert all fields like size, orientation, devicePixelRatio and etc to getters?
The getter's body will be able to subscribe to a feature specific event only.
class MediaQueryExample {
  final BuildContext context;

  const MediaQueryExample.of(this.context);

  Size get size => MediaQuery.of(context, MediaQueryAspect.size).size;
}
With that way, we can easy use MediaQueryExample like this:
// This code will not rebuild this widget cuz there is not any subscriptions
final mq = MediaQueryExample.of(context);

// After calling the size getter, MediaQueryExample subscribes to changes and will rebuild this widget when a size is changed
final size = mq.size;
By this way we will never face the issue @goderbauer talked about.

