The point of not caching is that we want to make sure that the same result is returned every time. If we decide to not test that, then why not just use the regular cache, instead of having two caches?

I think this does keep the same results is returned. If the existing _cachedIntrinsicDimensions is used as the sole cache for both the intrinsic checks and normal layout, there will be a subtle increase in the calls to markParentNeedsLayout (shown below) because _cachedIntrinsicDimensions will no longer be empty.



      flutter/packages/flutter/lib/src/rendering/box.dart


        Lines 2293 to 2308
      in
      a7f5fd5







           if ((_cachedBaselines != null && _cachedBaselines!.isNotEmpty) || 




               (_cachedIntrinsicDimensions != null && _cachedIntrinsicDimensions!.isNotEmpty) || 




               (_cachedDryLayoutSizes != null && _cachedDryLayoutSizes!.isNotEmpty)) { 




             // If we have cached data, then someone must have used our data. 




             // Since the parent will shortly be marked dirty, we can forget that they 




             // used the baseline and/or intrinsic dimensions. If they use them again, 




             // then we'll fill the cache again, and if we get dirty again, we'll 




             // notify them again. 




             _cachedBaselines?.clear(); 




             _cachedIntrinsicDimensions?.clear(); 




             _cachedDryLayoutSizes?.clear(); 




             if (parent is RenderObject) { 




               markParentNeedsLayout(); 




               return; 




             } 




           } 





As such, I opted to add a separate cache for these intrinsic checks to avoid changing the existing behavior.

I'm worried that caching is going to miss the exact types of bugs that led us to disable the cache in the first place though.

